    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1110177023" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1110177023" />
    <a title="Arathi Mohan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/17056482-arathi-mohan"><img alt="Arathi Mohan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1548162195p2/17056482.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1110177023?book_show_action=true">Nov 19, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Arathi Mohan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Arathi Mohan" href="/user/show/17056482-arathi-mohan">Arathi Mohan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17056482-arathi-mohan?shelf=india">india</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/17056482-arathi-mohan?shelf=non-fiction">non-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1110177023" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12948858504850286432">A real-life account of the harrowing exodus of the Kashmiri pandits from the valley in 1990. The author Rahul Pandita is a Red Cross award-winning news reporter for reporting from conflict zones like the Maoist hinterland in India(his book Hello, Bastar) and Kashmir. This time, he and his family are caught in the conflict. Leaving behind a 22-room house built with his father&apos;s hard-earned savings and Mother&apos;s bridal jewellery in Srinagar, his family is forced to migrate to Jammu, changing reside</span>
  <span id="freeText12948858504850286432" style="display:none">A real-life account of the harrowing exodus of the Kashmiri pandits from the valley in 1990. The author Rahul Pandita is a Red Cross award-winning news reporter for reporting from conflict zones like the Maoist hinterland in India(his book Hello, Bastar) and Kashmir. This time, he and his family are caught in the conflict. Leaving behind a 22-room house built with his father's hard-earned savings and Mother's bridal jewellery in Srinagar, his family is forced to migrate to Jammu, changing residences as many as twenty-two times. The author sees some dark times, losing a beloved brother to ruthless militants, watching his mother age prematurely and lose her voice due to the constant strain and worry and seeing his father wilt silently in the sadness of homelessness. They finally move to Delhi, where the author is currently working for the Open magazine. The book has many grim accounts of the author's family, friends and neighbours. But it ends on a hopeful note with the author firmly resolving that he will go back with his family to his homeland in the Kashmir valley. </span>
  <a data-text-id="12948858504850286432" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


